<subsection xml:id="subsection-1-3-4">
    <title>Exercises</title>
    <exercise xml:id="ex-1-3-1">
    <title>Find the Limits</title>
    <webwork>
      <pg-code>
        Context("Numeric");
        $a = list_random(3,4,5);
        $a2 = list_random(1..5);
        $b = list_random(2,3,4,5,6);
        $c = list_random(3,5,8);
        $d = list_random(5..9);
        $d2 = list_random(8..12);
        $f = list_random(6..11);
        $f2 = list_random(2..5);
        $f3 = Compute($f - $f2);
        $g = list_random(-2,-1, 1..3);
        $h = list_random(2..7);
        $j2 = list_random(5..9);
        $j3 = list_random(3..6);
        
        $ans_a_value = exp(-$a*2 + $a2) + sqrt(2);
        $ans_a = Compute($ans_a_value);
        $ans_a_rounded = sprintf("%.3f", $ans_a_value);
        $ans_b = Compute(0);
        $ans_c = Infinity;
        $ans_d = Compute(-$d/$d2);
        $ans_e = Compute(0);
        $ans_f = Compute(0);
        $ans_g = Compute(0);
        $ans_h = Compute(0);
        $ans_i = Compute(1);
        $ans_j = Infinity;
        $a_display = ($a == 1) ? "" : "$a";
        $b_display = ($b &lt; 0) ? "- " . abs($b) : "+ " . $b;
        $c_display = ($c &lt; 0) ? "- " . abs($c) : "+ " . $c;
      </pg-code>

      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the following limits.  Enter "INF" or "-INF" for <m>\infty</m> or <m>-\infty</m>.  Round answers to at least three decimal places.
        </p>

        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <md>
                            \lim_{x\rightarrow 2} e^{-<var name = "$a"/>x + <var name = "$a2"/>} + \sqrt{x}
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Answer: <var name="$ans_a" width="10"/>
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        <md>
                            \lim_{x\rightarrow \infty} x^2e^{-<var name = "$b"/>x}
                        </md>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Answer: <var name="$ans_b" width="10"/>
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        <md>
                            \lim_{x\rightarrow <var name = "$c"/>} \frac{5}{(x-<var name = "$c"/>)^4}
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Answer: <var name="$ans_c" width="10"/>
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        <md>
                            \lim_{x\rightarrow -\infty} \frac{<var name = "$d"/> x^6 - 3x^2 + x + 3}{-<var name = "$d2"/> x^6 + x^3 - 11x^2}
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Answer: <var name="$ans_d" width="10"/>
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        <md>
                            \lim_{x\rightarrow \infty} x^n e^{-ax} \text{ where } n,a > 0
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Answer: <var name="$ans_e" width="10"/>
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        <md>
                            \lim_{x\rightarrow -\infty} \frac{e^{<var name = "$f"/>x}}{e^{<var name = "$f2"/>x}}
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Answer: <var name="$ans_f" width="10"/>
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        <md>
                            \lim_{x\rightarrow \infty} \frac{\ln(x^5)-<var name = "$g"/> x}{x^3}
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Answer: <var name="$ans_g" width="10"/>
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        <md>
                            \lim_{x\rightarrow \infty} 3^{-<var name = "$h"/>x + 1}
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Answer: <var name="$ans_h" width="10"/>
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        <md>
                            \lim_{x\rightarrow \infty} e^{\frac{1}{x^2}}
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Answer: <var name="$ans_i" width="10"/>
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        <md>
                            \lim_{x\rightarrow -\infty} \frac{x-<var name = "$j2"/>x^3}{<var name = "$j3"/>x^2 - 3x + 1}
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Answer: <var name="$ans_j" width="10"/>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The function is continuous at <m>x=2</m>.
                        So, we can plug <m>2</m> in to get
                        <m>e^{-<var name = "$a"/>\cdot 2 + <var name = "$a2"/>} + \sqrt{2} \approx <var name = "$ans_a_rounded"/></m>
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        Exponentials dominator polynomials.
                        <m>\lim_{x\rightarrow} e^{-<var name = "$b"/>x} 0.</m> 
                        So, the whole limit is <m>0</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        On both sides of <m>x=<var name = "$c"/></m>, the function grows to positive infinity as 
                        <m>x</m> approaches <m><var name = "$d"/></m>.
                        So, the limit is <m>\infinity</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        We have two polynomials of equal degres (6).
                        So, the limit is the ratio of the leading coefficients:
                        <m>\frac{<var name = "$d"/>}{-<var name = "d2"/>} = -\frac{<var name = "$d"/>}{<var name = "d2"/>} </m>
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        Exponentials dominate polynomials.  So, we look at <m>e^{-ax}</m>,
                        which goes to <m>0</m>.
                        So, the limit is <m>0</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        We can simplify the function as <m>e^{(<var name = "$f"/> - <var name = "$f2"/>)x} = e^{<var name = "e3"/>x}</m>.
                        As <m>x</m> approaches negative infinity, this approaches <m>0</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        The numerator has both logaritmic and polynomial elements.
                        Since polynomials dominiate logarithms, we can think of the numerator as behaving like a polynomial of degree <m>1</m> at <m>\pm \infty</m>.
                        The denominator is a higher-degree polynomial.  So, it dominates.
                        Thus, the limit is <m>0</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        The exponent goes to <m>-\infty</m>.
                        <m>3^y</m> approaches 0 as <m>y</m> goes to <m>-infty</m>.
                        So, the limit is <m>0</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        The exponent goes to <m>0</m>.
                        So, the limit is <m>e^0 = 1</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        The numerator dominates since it has higher degree.
                        So, the limit will be positive or negative infinity.
                        We need to determine which.
                        The denominator is led by <m><var name = "$j3"/>x^2</m>, which goes to positive infinity as <m>x</m> approaches negative infinity.
                        The numerator is led by <m>-<var name = "$j2"/>x^3</m>, which goes to positive infinity as <m>x</m> approaches negative infinity.
                        So, we have <m>\frac{\text{positive}}{\text{positive}} = \text{positive}</m>.
                        So, the limit is <m>\infty</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </webwork>
  </exercise>

</subsection>